Lithium-ion batteries: Light, high energy density, long lifespan. {'textbook_id': 'vrg4sz0c13', 'chapter_id': 'ttlowzex6r', 'content': '8.  What is the *solid electrolyte interface*? Why is it a good target\n    for investigation by nanoengineers?'}

The solid electrolyte interface (SEI) is a thin protective layer formed on the surface of the negative electrode of a lithium-ion battery. It is created when the electrolyte decomposes, and it allows ions to pass but blocks electrons, which affects the stability and life of the battery.
